Question 2

[1] "Which of the seven beliefs concerned you the most, and why?"
 [1] The seventh belief, “depending on men”, because I think this is the most unreasonable thought for women.                                                                                                     
 [2]                                                                                                                                                                                                              
 [3]                                                                                                                                                                                                              
 [4] “Be quiet” was the most concerning to me. If I can’t speak up in any situation, I can’t choose anything that I want, Also I can’t protect myself from other dangers.                                         
 [5] I thought “be quiet, dear,” would be appropriate. This is because when I was little, if I made too much noise, I would be scolded immediately for being quiet.                                               
 [6]                                                                                                                                                                                                              
 [7] Don’t trust women Reason: I have experienced problems with women.                                                                                                                                            
 [8] I was most concerned about habit seven because it was very scary to be dependent on man.                                                                                                                     
 [9] I think “Good women suffer in silence” is most concerning, because everyone feels pain and stress, and it builds up. Suffering silence is bad for their body and mental health.                              
[10] I think “Be a people pleaser” is the most concerned me. It is because, I was often said “Stay in a good mood!”, but it was not said for boy. I was thought that girl should stay in a good mood by my family.

Question 3

[1] "How does her talk apply to you?"
 [1] I noticed that if we want to change the situations, we have to change not only ourselves, but also people around us because I always think that “Only changing myself is going to work well” and most of the time it doesn't work well.                                                                                                                                                                                         
 [2] Answer 3: Her talk applies to me in that girls are often expected to please others however they feel or whatever happens to them. I may have that kind of tendency, and I often see girls making efforts to please others, especially men; this kind of situation is considered to be welcome and widely accepted. I think everyone needs to be aware of the ridiculous situation and start to speak up when something is wrong.
 [3] In her talk, she said mothers teach their daughters to speak softly. I have experienced something like that in my childhood. That teaching made some stereotypes in my mind. Mothers’ words have a huge influence on their daughters. But I think in India, not only their mothers but also others say that to girls. Those social movements forced womens’ ideas so much I think.                                              
 [4] >I think it is hard for women in India to be forced to become good women. What is the meaning of “good” woman? I cannot understand why Indian people think women should be gentle. There is still gender discrimination in Japan, but it is much more right than India’s enforcement about women.                                                                                                                               
 [5] To change the image of good women or men                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        
 [6] In Japan, it is still difficult for women to express their opinions, so I thought her talk was similar in that women’s position is still not equal to that of men.

 [2]                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     
 [3]

 [6] When I was in kindergarten, teachers asked us to “choose your favourite colours of hat” . I chose the blue one, but the other girls chose the pink one. Then my friends cheated on me. That time I thought I “should” choose the pink one, and the boy “should” choose the blue one.

The seven habits are “turning off your body” “being quiet” “becoming a person who pleases people” “not having sexuality” “not trusting women” “having a duty to your desires” and “being dependent on men.” In order to change this social foundation, it is important to make adjustments so that women can enter the workforce and have an equal position with men.This is something that requires training. Nowadays, women are more advanced in society than in the past, but I feel that the women who make bento boxes and the women that men are looking for have not changed more than anything else. "I want a woman who can do housework" and "I want a woman who always smiles" are opinions that are often seen among men today, and women are living their lives in accordance with them. However, I feel that it is different to ask for a woman like this. It is okay for men to do housework, and I feel that it is wrong to have a society where men are praised just for doing housework.

Also, many women complain about accepting education. I think it gives women the power of living without men’s help.
